How well ?<br>
<br>
That's a BIG plus, depending on how well you speak it already.  For some reason, I'd guessed earlier that you were a total beginner.<br>
<br>
In Hawaii, you can easily find low-paying ($10 per hour) work...again, depending on your fluency.<br>
<br>
An associate's (2-year) degree isn't good enough for a regular work-visa in Japan.  You need a 4-year degree.<br>
<br>
I know people who came here on the strength of a forged degree, but can't promise that'll work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=higakun>higakun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://komplx.com/higan/Page_2/IMAG000.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/16/03 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://images.warcry.com/image.php?id=4964 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oh, you already speak Japanese.</span><hr size=1> elementry level lol. like i said i cant practice talking with anyone. so it really hinders me. but its good to know about the four year degree thing. so would it then be feasible to attend school in japan under a foreign learning program and while there recieve a 4 year then apply for a work visa? also without a work visa, can i still work in places like english teaching? so i can pay for college and stuff. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/22/03 11:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oh, you already speak Japanese.</span><hr size=1> yes you can get a 4 year degree in japan and then get a work visa.  as long as you have a valid 4 year degree is all that really matters, not so much where you get it from.  You are not technically allowed to work in eikaiwa (english teaching) schools, or anywhere, really, for that matter, without a work visa (though you might be permitted a small on-campus job with a student visa, you`ll have to check online) but many foreigners do it under the table - the best bet is to get private students as there`s very little risk, and anyway, most schools will not touch you with a 10 foot pole if you have no work visa - there are simply too many foreigners out there <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>with</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> valid work visas to bother with the risk.<br>
<br>
as an aside, and i don`t want to be rude, but you will need a lot more than elementary japanese to do anything vaugely related to japan/japanese translation (other than english teaching).  The competition is very stiff, and japanese is a suprisingly popular language, especially out here in asia/oceania - i would easily say that 50% of my foreign friends out here have what can be considered an &quot;elementary level&quot; of japanese (especially spoken) - this is in addition to solid 4 year degrees in specialized subjects like business/science/engineering, etc.  So study up now, while you`re still young! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu. </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
